# Chair44 Game Website - Cursor Rules

## Project Overview
Chair44 is a collection of browser-based games with a minimalist design inspired by neal.fun.

## Tech Stack
- Next.js 16 (App Router)
- React 19
- TypeScript
- Tailwind CSS 4

## Code Style & Conventions

### TypeScript
- Use TypeScript for all new files
- Define interfaces for all data structures
- Prefer `interface` over `type` for object shapes
- Use explicit return types for functions when not obvious
- Avoid `any` types - use `unknown` if type is truly unknown

### React Components
- Use functional components with hooks
- Prefer named exports for pages, default exports are fine for page.tsx files
- Use Server Components by default (Next.js App Router)
- Only add 'use client' when necessary (state, effects, browser APIs)
- Keep components focused and single-purpose

### Naming Conventions
- Components: PascalCase (e.g., `GameCard.tsx`)
- Files: kebab-case for utilities (e.g., `game-utils.ts`)
- Variables/functions: camelCase (e.g., `handleClick`, `gameData`)
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (e.g., `MAX_SCORE`)
- CSS classes: Use Tailwind utility classes

### File Structure
```
app/
  ├── page.tsx              # Home page with game grid
  ├── layout.tsx            # Root layout
  ├── globals.css           # Global styles
  └── games/
      └── [id]/
          └── page.tsx      # Individual game pages
components/
  ├── ui/                   # Reusable UI components
  └── games/                # Game-specific components
lib/
  └── utils.ts              # Utility functions
```

## Design System

### Colors
- Background: White (#ffffff) / Dark Black (#0a0a0a)
- Text Primary: Black (#000000) / White (#ededed)
- Text Secondary: Gray-600 / Gray-400
- Borders: Gray-200 / Gray-800
- Accent: Blue-600 / Blue-400 (for hovers and active states)

### Typography
- Font Family: Geist Sans (primary), Geist Mono (code)
- Headings: Bold, use semantic sizing (text-4xl, text-2xl, etc.)
- Body: Regular weight, text-base or text-lg
- Line height: leading-relaxed for body text

### Spacing
- Use Tailwind's spacing scale (4, 6, 8, 12, etc.)
- Consistent padding: p-6 or p-8 for cards
- Consistent gaps: gap-4 for grids

### Components
- Cards: Border, rounded-lg, padding-8
- Hover states: Always include subtle transitions
- Focus states: Ensure keyboard navigation is clear
- Responsive: Mobile-first approach (md: for desktop)

## UI Patterns

### Game Cards
- Display emoji icon (text-4xl)
- Title (text-2xl, font-semibold)
- Description (text-gray-600)
- Hover effects: border color change, shadow-lg, emoji scale-110
- Link to /games/[id]

### Layout
- Max width: max-w-6xl
- Horizontal padding: px-6
- Vertical padding: py-8 or py-12

### Dark Mode
- Always include dark mode variants
- Use dark: prefix for Tailwind classes
- Test both light and dark modes

## Best Practices

### Performance
- Use Next.js Image component for images
- Lazy load heavy components
- Minimize client-side JavaScript
- Use Server Components when possible

### Accessibility
- Use semantic HTML elements
- Include alt text for images
- Ensure keyboard navigation works
- Maintain good color contrast ratios

### Code Organization
- Keep files under 300 lines when possible
- Extract reusable logic into hooks or utilities
- Co-locate related components
- Group imports: React/Next, third-party, local

### Git Commits
- Use clear, descriptive commit messages
- Format: "verb: description" (e.g., "feat: add snake game")
- Keep commits focused and atomic

## Game Development Guidelines

### New Game Checklist
1. Add game entry to games array in app/page.tsx
2. Create game page at app/games/[id]/page.tsx
3. Include back button to home
4. Add game instructions
5. Implement responsive design
6. Test on mobile and desktop
7. Ensure dark mode compatibility

### Game Page Structure
- Header with game title and back button
- Game canvas/container
- Instructions section
- Score display (if applicable)
- Restart/reset button

### State Management
- Use useState for simple local state
- Use useReducer for complex game state
- Consider context for shared state across components
- Keep game logic separate from UI components

## Testing & Quality

### Before Committing
- Check for TypeScript errors
- Run linter (npm run lint)
- Test in both light and dark modes
- Test on mobile viewport
- Verify all links work

### Code Review Focus
- Type safety
- Accessibility
- Performance implications
- Code readability
- Consistency with style guide

## Common Patterns to Follow

### Link Component Usage
```tsx
import Link from "next/link";

<Link href="/path" className="...">
  Content
</Link>
```

### Conditional Dark Mode Classes
```tsx
className="bg-white dark:bg-black text-black dark:text-white"
```

### Game Data Interface
```tsx
interface Game {
  id: string;
  title: string;
  description: string;
  emoji: string;
}
```

## What to Avoid
- Inline styles (use Tailwind classes)
- Magic numbers (define constants)
- Deep component nesting (flatten when possible)
- Overly complex components (split into smaller ones)
- Hardcoded values (use constants or config)
- Missing TypeScript types
- Ignoring dark mode
- Non-semantic HTML (use proper elements)

